				<exercises>
 					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS"/>, Section 1.2, Exercise 1.2.1.) </p></aside>
							Which of the following equations are linear?
							<ol marker="[a]" cols="2">
								<li>
									<m>2x-3y+4z =-10</m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>2.123x_1+5.541x_2-9.101x_3 = 11.012</m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>x^2 +y^2 +z^2 =1</m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x+4^3y = \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{3} \right)</m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>x +yz =3</m>
							</li></ol>							
						</statement>
						 <hint xml:id = "def-linear-equation">
						 	A <em> linear equation </em> is an equation of the form,
						 	<me>
						 		a_1 x_1 + a_2 x_2 + \ldots + a_n x_n = b.
						 	</me>
						 	Where <m> a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n </m> and <m> b </m> are scalars and <m> x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n </m> are the variables of the equation.  
						</hint> 
						<solution>
						<ol marker="[a]">
						<li>
						The equation  <m> 2x -3y + 4z = -10 </m> is a linear equation because it is of the form given in <xref ref = "def-linear-equation"/> where <m> 2, -3, 4, -10 </m> are scalars and <m> x,y, z </m> are variables. 
						</li>
						<li>
						The equation  <m>2.123x_1+5.541x_2-9.101x_3 = 11.012</m> is a linear equation because it is of the form given in <xref ref = "def-linear-equation"/> where <m> 2.123, 5.541, 9.101, 11.012 </m> are scalars and <m> x_1,x_2, x_3 </m> are variables. 
						</li>
						<li>
						The equation  <m>x^2 +y^2 +z^2 =1</m> is a not a linear equation because it is not of the form given in <xref ref = "def-linear-equation"/>.  The equation contains the variables <m> x,y, z </m> squared.  
						</li>
						<li>
						The equation  <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x+4^3y = \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{3} \right)</m> is a liner equation because it is of the form given in <xref ref = "def-linear-equation"/> where <m> \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, 4^3,  \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)</m> are scalars and <m> x,y </m> are variables. 
						</li>
						<li>
						The equation  <m>x +yz =3</m> is a not a liner equation because it is not of the form given in <xref ref = "def-linear-equation"/>.  The equation contains a product of the variables <m> y, z. </m> 
						</li>
						</ol>
						</solution> 
						<answer>
							<ol marker="[a]" cols="2">
								<li>
									Linear.
								</li>
								<li>
									Linear.
								</li>
								<li>
									Not linear.
								</li>
								<li>
								 Linear.
								</li>
								<li>
								 Not linear.
								</li>
							</ol>
						</answer> 
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement> <aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS"/>, Section 1.2, Exercise 1.2.2.) </p></aside>
							Consider the system of equations		
							<md>
								<mrow>
									x + 2y +3z +4w \amp =4
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									x+y + z +w \amp =2
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									x+ 2y +2z +w \amp =2
								</mrow>
							</md>
							For each of the following tuples <m>(x,y,z,w)</m> of real numbers, determine whether it is a solution of the first equation, second equation, and/or third equation. Which ones are solutions to the system of equations? 
								<ol marker="[a]" cols="3">
									<li>
									 	<m>(2,0,-2,2)</m> 
									</li>
									<li>
										<m>(2,2,-2,0)</m>
									</li>
									<li>
										<m>(1,1,-1,1)</m>
									</li>
									<li>
										<m>(3,0,-1,1)</m>
									</li>
									<li>
										<m>(2,-2,2,0)</m>
									</li>
								</ol>		
							
							</statement>
							<hint xml:id= "solution-to-equation">
							A <em> solution </em> to an equation is a tuple of values that make the equation true when the values are substituted for their respective variables within the equation.
							</hint>
							<hint xml:id= "solution-to-system">
							A <em> solution </em> to a system of equations must satisfy <em> all </em> equations in the system. 
							</hint>
							<answer>
								<ol marker="[a]">			
									<li>
										The tuple <m> (2,0,-2,2) </m> is a solution to the first and second equation but not the third equation.  It is not a solution to the system of equations.
									</li>
									<li>
										The tuple <m> (2,2,-2,0) </m> is a solution to the second and third equation but not the first equation.  It is not a solution to the system of equations.
									</li>
									<li>
										The tuple <m> (1,1,-1,1) </m> is a solution to all three equations and hence is a solution to the system of equations.
									</li>
									<li>
										The tuple <m> (3,0,-1,1) </m> is a solution to the first and third equations but not the second equation.  It is not a solution to the system of equations.
									</li>
									<li>
										The tuple <m> (2,-2,2,0) </m> is a solution to all three equations and hence is a solution to the system of equations.
									</li>
								</ol>
							</answer>
							<solution>
								<ol marker="[a]">
									<li>
										Substituting in <m>x =2, y = 0, z=-2</m> and <m> w=2 </m> into the equation:
										<me> 2 + 2(0) + 3(-2) + 4(2) = 4 </me>
										This equation is true.  Therefore <m> (2,0,-2,2) </m> is a solution to the first equation.  Similarly, 
										<me> 2 + 0 + (-2) + 2 = 2 </me>
										The above result is also true, therefore the tuple is a solution to the second equation.  Lastly,
										<me> 2 + 2(0) + 2(-2) +2 = 2</me>
										The above result is false, because 0 is not equal to 2.  Therefore, the tuple is not a solution of the last equation. The tuple <m> (2,0,-2,2) </m> is not a solution to the system of equations because it is not a solution to all three equations. 
									</li>
								</ol>
							</solution>
						</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS"/>, Section 1.1, Exercise 1.1.1.) </p></aside>
							Graphically, find the solution to the system <m>x+3y =1</m> and <m>x-y=3</m>.  That is, each of these equations is a line in the plane.  Graph each line and see where they intersect.
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id = "graphing-a-line"> Two points make a line, so we may simply find two solutions of each equation, graph them, and connect the two solutions to form a line.     
						</hint> 
						<answer>
							<image source="chp2-1q5.png"/>
							The lines intersect at the point <m> (2.5, -.5) .</m>
							</answer>
						<solution>  We may start with the line <m>x+3y =1.</m> First notice that setting <m> y = 0 </m> gives <m> x = 1. </m> And setting <m> x = 4 </m> we get a whole number solution  <m> y = -1.</m>   The following graph is obtained by plotting these two solutions, <m> (1,0), (4,-1) </m> and connecting them to form a line. 
						<image source = "chp2-1q5sol1.png"/>
						Similarly, for the second equation we find the solutions <m>(0,-3), (3,0) </m>, plot them on the same set of axes as the first line, and connect the two points to form a line.  
						<image source = "chp2-1q5sol2.png"/>
						The solution to the system of equations is the point of intersection of the lines, which we can graphically approximate to be <m> (2.5, -.5) .</m>  We can check this solution by plugging it back into both equations.  

						<md> 
							<mrow>
							2.5 + 3(-.5) = 1
						</mrow>
						<mrow>
							2.5 - (-.5) = 3.
						</mrow>
						</md> 
						</solution> 


					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS"/>, Section 1.1, Exercise 1.1.2.) </p></aside>
							Graphically, find the point of intersection of the two lines <m>3x+y =3</m> and <m>x+2y=1</m>.  That is, graph each line and see where they intersect.
						</statement>
						<hint> Referring to <xref ref = "graphing-a-line"/>, two points make a line, so we may simply find two solutions of each equation, graph them, and connect the two solutions to form a line.     
						</hint> 
						<answer>
							<image source="chp2-1q6.png"/>
							The lines intersect at the point <m> (1, 0) .</m>
							</answer>
					<solution>  We may start with the line <m>3x+y =3.</m> First notice that setting <m> y = 0 </m> gives <m> x = 1. </m> And setting <m> x = 0 </m> we get <m> y = 3.</m>   The following graph is obtained by plotting these two solutions, <m> (1,0), (0,3) </m> and connecting them to form a line. 
						<image source = "chp2-1q6sol1.png"/>
						Similarly, for the second equation we find the solutions <m>(1,0), (0,.5) </m>, plot them on the same set of axes as the first line, and connect the two points to form a line.  
						<image source = "chp2-1q6sol2.png"/>
						The solution to the system of equations is the point of intersection of the lines, which we can graphically approximate to be <m> (1, 0) .</m>  We can check this solution by plugging it back into both equations.  

						<md> 
							<mrow>
							3(1) + 0 = 3
						</mrow>
						<mrow>
							1 - 0= 1. 
						</mrow>
						</md> 
						</solution> 		
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise xml:id = "exercise-back-substitution"><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS"/>, Section 1.3, Exercise 1.3.5.) </p></aside>
							Solve for the following system by back substitution.
							<md>
								<mrow>
									x+3y -2z \amp =5
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									y + 3z \amp =4
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									z \amp  =1
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id= "back-substitution">
						 	Work your way from the bottom equation to the top. Try first Substituting the value of <m> z </m> into the second equation to solve for <m> y </m>.   
						</hint> 
						<answer>
							<me> x=4,y=1,z=1</me>
						</answer>
						<solution>
							Let's follow the hint and substitute <m> z =1 </m> in the second equation.
							<me> y + 3(1) = 4</me>
							Solving for <m> y, </m> by subtracting 3 from both sides, yields <m> y = 1 .</m>  Now, we may substitute <m> z= 1 </m> and <m> y = 1 </m> into the first equation to solve for <m> x</m>.
							<me> x + 3(1) -2(1) = 5 </me>
							Solving for <m> x, </m> by subtracting 1 from both sides, yields <m> x = 4 </m>.  The solution to the system of equations is <m> x=4,y=1,z=1</m>
						</solution>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 1.1, Exercise 1.1.17.) </p></aside>
							Write the augmented matrix for each of the following systems of linear equations.
							<ol marker="[a]" cols="2">								
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											 x - 3y \amp = 5
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 2x + y \amp = 5 
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											x - 2y \amp = 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 
											 y \amp = 5
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											x - y + z \amp = \amp 2
										</mrow>
										<mrow>											 
											x - z \amp = \amp 1
										</mrow>
										<mrow>											 
											 y + 2z \amp = \amp 0
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											x + y \amp = \amp 1
										</mrow>
										<mrow>											 
											 y + z \amp = \amp 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>											 
											-x  + z \amp = \amp 2
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
							 </ol>
						</statement>
						<hint>
						An <em> augmented matrix </em> of a system of <m> n </m> variables contains the coefficients of the variables in the first <m> n-1 </m> columns and contains the constant terms in the final column.   The vertical bar separating the first <m> n-1 </m> columns from the final column serves as a reminder of the equal sign in the equations of the system.  
						</hint>
						<answer>
							<ol marker="[a]" cols="2">								
								<li>
									<me>\matr{cc|c}{1\amp -3\amp 5\\2\amp 1\amp 5} </me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me>\matr{cc|c}{1\amp -2\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 5} </me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> \matr{ccc|c}{1\amp -1\amp 1 \amp 2 \\1\amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\ 0\amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0} </me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<me> \matr{ccc|c}{1\amp 1\amp 0 \amp 1 \\0\amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ -1\amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 2} 
									</me>
								</li>
							 </ol>
						</answer> 
						<!-- <solution>
						</solution> -->
					</exercise></p>
